No module federation. No shared bundler config. Just Angular 21 and a trick that’s been hiding in your browser all along.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Hero Image of Micro FrontendHere’s a problem almost every growing product hits sooner or later. You build a nice UI widget — a checkout card, a chat bubble, a booking form — and suddenly other teams want it too. One team runs React. Another runs Vue. Marketing has a WordPress site. Do you really rewrite the same widget three times?
This is the problem micro frontends try to solve: split the UI into pieces that separate teams can build, deploy, and own independently. If you’ve researched the topic, you’ve probably run into module federation — a bundler feature that lets separately-built apps share code at runtime. It works, but it’s heavy machinery: every team needs compatible bundler setups, framework versions have to stay in sync, and the configuration alone has eaten more than one of my weekends.
So this weekend I tried the other path: compile an Angular component into a native web component — a custom HTML tag the browser itself understands, no framework needed on the host page. Any site — React, Vue, WordPress, a plain HTML file from 2009 — can consume it like a regular DOM element.
And Angular 21 turned out to be the best version yet for this. Zoneless change detection is now the default, which means the thing that always made Angular Elements feel heavy — shipping zone.js and its monkey-patched world into someone else’s page — is just… gone. Here’s the whole build, start to finish. Every snippet below is from a project I actually ran, and the final widget is one deployable JavaScript file.

Why web components for micro frontends?
Quick alignment before code. Whatever tool you pick, the hard part of micro frontends is always the seam — the boundary where the host app loads your widget and talks to it. Module federation puts that seam inside the bundler, which is why everyone has to agree on tooling.
Web components put the seam at the browser level instead. The seam is the DOM itself — the one API every website already shares:

• The host writes — just HTML.

• Data goes in through attributes and properties.

• Data comes out through CustomEvents.

• The host doesn’t know or care that Angular is inside
The trade-off is real too — each widget ships its own copy of the framework runtime. We’ll get to that at the end, with numbers.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Architecture of Micro FrontendArchitecture: the widget team builds an Angular 21 component into a single main.js on a CDN; host pages in any framework consume it through the DOM seam — attributes in, CustomEvents out.
The whole architecture in one picture: the widget team owns everything on the left, hosts own everything on the right, and the only thing they share is the DOM.

Why Angular 21 changes the math
Two things landed in v21 that matter here:
Zoneless is the default. New Angular 21 projects don’t include zone.js at all. For a normal app that’s a nice-to-have. For a web component it’s huge, because zone.js patches global browser APIs — setTimeout, Promise, event listeners. Injecting that into a host page you don’t own was always the sketchiest part of Angular Elements. Now your widget only rerenders when a signal it depends on changes. No global patching, no 30 kB tax.
Signals are the whole story now. If you’re newer to Angular: a signal is just a reactive value — you read it by calling it (price()), you change it with .set() or .update(), and anything that depends on it updates automatically. With input(), output(), and computed(), the whole component model works this way now — and it lines up neatly with how custom elements work: attribute changes flow into signal inputs, and change detection just follows the graph.
Step 1: Scaffold
npx @angular/cli@21 new checkout-widget --style=css --ssr=false
cd checkout-widget
npm install @angular/elementsNo flags needed for zoneless — in v21 it’s the default. (If you ever want zone.js back, you have to opt in with provideZoneChangeDetection(). Feels good that the arrow points that way now.)
The widget we’re building is a tiny checkout card: product name and price come in from the host, quantity is internal state, and clicking “Checkout” fires an event back out. Small, but it exercises every part of the seam — data in, state inside, events out.
Step 2: The component
src/app/checkout-widget.ts:
import { Component, computed, input, output, signal } from '@angular/core';export interface CheckoutPayload {
product: string;
quantity: number;
total: number;
}
@Component({
// No selector — this component only ever lives as a custom element,
// and the tag name comes from customElements.define() instead.
template: `
<div class="card">
<h3>{{ product() }}</h3>
<p class="price">{{ price() }} {{ currency() }}</p>
<div class="qty">
<button (click)="decrease()" [disabled]="quantity() === 1">−</button>
<span>{{ quantity() }}</span>
<button (click)="increase()">+</button>
</div>
<button class="checkout" (click)="checkout()">
Checkout — {{ total() }} {{ currency() }}
</button>
</div>
`,
})
export class CheckoutWidget {
// Attributes coming from the host page (always strings in HTML!)
product = input('Unknown product');
price = input(0, { transform: Number });
currency = input('USD')
// Internal state
quantity = signal(1);
total = computed(() => this.quantity() * this.price());
// Becomes a native CustomEvent on the web component
checkedOut = output<CheckoutPayload>();
increase() {
this.quantity.update((q) => q + 1);
}
decrease() {
this.quantity.update((q) => Math.max(1, q - 1));
}
checkout() {
this.checkedOut.emit({
product: this.product(),
quantity: this.quantity(),
total: this.total(),
});
}
}
(I stripped the styles for readability — put whatever you want in styles.)
Two details here that will save you a debugging session:
transform: Number on the price input. HTML attributes are always strings. Without the transform, price=”89" arrives as “89”, and quantity() * price() does JavaScript stringmath chaos. With signal inputs, the fix is one option instead of a getter/setter dance. This alone is a reason to like the new API for Elements work.
output() becomes a real CustomEvent. When Angular Elements wraps this component, checkedOut isn’t an RxJS thing the host needs to understand — it’s dispatched as a native CustomEvent named checkedOut, with your payload in event.detail. The host just uses addEventListener. That’s the entire contract.
Step 3: Register it as a custom element
This is where it stops being an app. Replace src/main.ts entirely:
import { createApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { createCustomElement } from '@angular/elements';
import { CheckoutWidget } from './app/checkout-widget';
(async () => {
// No bootstrapApplication here — we are not booting an app,
// we are registering a web component.
const app = await createApplication({
providers: [],
}); const checkoutElement = createCustomElement(CheckoutWidget, {
injector: app.injector,
});
customElements.define('pip-checkout', checkoutElement);
})();
The mental model shift: bootstrapApplication says “Angular owns this page.” createApplication says “give me an Angular environment, I’ll decide what to do with it.” We use it to mint a custom element class and hand it to the browser’s own registry.
You can register multiple widgets from one bundle — call createCustomElement + customElements.define once per component, sharing the same injector.
One rule from the custom elements spec: the tag name must contain a dash. pip-checkout works, checkout will throw. Prefix with your team or product name; that’s your namespace.
Step 4: Build it
ng build — output-hashing=none— output-hashing=none gives you a stable main.js instead of main.C3PO4R2D2.js, so host pages can reference a fixed URL. Here’s my actual build output:
Initial chunk files | Names | Raw size | Estimated transfer size main.js | main | 111.79 kB | 33.30 kB Application bundle generation complete. [3.570 seconds]
For this small widget, that’s 33 kB over the wire — a fully reactive Angular component, no zone.js anywhere. Your number will grow with the features you build in (forms, HTTP, animations all add weight), but for context, that baseline is smaller than most hero images. I remember when an Angular Elements bundle started as a 200 kB+ conversation with your tech lead. Zoneless by default plus years of tree-shaking work ended that argument.
Ship dist/checkout-widget/browser/main.js to any static host or CDN. That file is your micro frontend. Versioning, deployment, rollback — all just static file management, owned by your team alone.
Step 5: Use it anywhere
This is the part I keep showing people. A plain HTML page — no Angular, no build step:
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<body>
<h1>I'm a plain HTML page 👋</h1>
<pip-checkout
product="Mechanical Keyboard"
price="89"
currency="USD">
</pip-checkout>
<script src="https://cdn.your-team.dev/checkout-widget/main.js"></script>
<script>
document
.querySelector('pip-checkout')
.addEventListener('checkedOut', (event) => {
console.log('Host received:', event.detail);
// { product: "Mechanical Keyboard", quantity: 2, total: 178 }
});
</script>
</body>
</html>That’s it. The host page speaks HTML and DOM events — two of the most stable APIs on the web. The same tag works inside React (<pip-checkout product={name} /> plus a ref for the event listener), Vue, Svelte, or a server-rendered template from any backend.
I verified the whole loop before writing this: element registers, attributes flow in as signals, clicking + bumps the internal quantity signal, and checkedOut fires with { quantity: 2, total: 178 }. Data in through attributes, state inside through signals, data out through events. Clean seam.
